segments.text: This is side number three.

Picking up on the comments about the cooperation between Arizona and California on the interstate highway location, I think that was perhaps one of the highlights of the effort because there were some sharp differences of opinion about freeway location.
as felt in the local community.
These didn't seem to have to do too much with the often cited problems of accessibility to the freeway.
It was more a matter of what property might be adversely affected and things of that sort.
The other factor, though, that actually was a major factor on the California side in the location of the freeway was the fact that the lower Colorado River Indian Reservation,
lay directly across the Colorado River from the city of Yuma.
And it was necessary for the California Highway Department to go through part of the Indian Reservation with the interstate highway.
There was also a town of sorts, a village, directly across to the north of downtown Yuma, which caused part of the problem, and there were some very

sharp differences of opinion amongst the Indians as to whether or not, because of certain treaty situations, they should even allow a federal agency or a state agency to come in and preempt part of their land.
And the feelings ran pretty high.
In fact, so high that in a few years earlier, when one of the
members of that tribe, while working for the post office in Yuma, had risen to the position of the assistant postmaster, the tribe disowned him because he was working for the federal government.
And they saw the federal government as being an enemy, if you would, of the tribe.
And so they would not have anything to do with him.
He was literally shunned by the rest of the tribe because of the position.
That was near the close of the time that I was in Yuma.
I was there from, let's see, 1958 to 1962.
One of the things, though, that was of extreme interest to me during 1959 and into 1960 was that I had a man by the name of William Wisner
of the ISNER, who was from Michigan, had moved down.
His wife was working for the county extension office as a home demonstration agent.
And he was picked up on a release time by the city and county to direct the census operations in the southern part of Yuma County.
The planning department became very much a part of the effort in making a lot of decisions about census enumeration in Yuma County as a result of that.
And Whistler had lots to say.
And his boss was in Phoenix, so it was really a very strong relationship that we had, including
resolving some problems between the lower Colorado River Indians and the Kokopas.
The Kokopas occupied a very small reservation of about 300 acres, located along the edge of the Yuma Mesa on the southwest part of Yuma.
That, plus some experiences that Wisner had when he went up to work in northern Arizona on the Navajo

reservation in dealing with the Indian tribes really gave me a much greater appreciation for some of the problems of the American Indian when the Indians themselves were both experiencing the need to move themselves as well as being confronted with urban expansion onto reservation lands.
And of course, in Arizona, New Mexico, California, Nevada, this has become
much more of a serious issue.
In Oklahoma?
Yeah.
Well, in Oklahoma, except the reservations in Oklahoma are so few.
But when you get to the Arizona, you have these tremendous.
But the one in Tulsa is not.
Right.
That's right.
So that was perhaps one of the other highlights.
The third being that we were able to get airport zoning regulations adopted in Yuma County to protect the field
there at Yuma, which was also jointly used initially by Army and then by Marine Corps as a Marine Corps auxiliary air station.
What happened to the freeway debate between the two state agencies?
Actually, the two state agencies were in very good agreement with each other.
The problems were the conflicts between the general issue of federal government and
and treaty lands that the Indians held, and the concerns that the local community had about access to and from the freeway.
And the building of that route ultimately followed pretty much what the planning staff had concurred with with respect to the highway location.
Did that go north of the territorial prison?
It went.
Well, OK, the territorial prison is at the northeast corner of downtown.
And it went alongside the territorial prison just to the east of that, swept along the Mesa edge overlooking the Yuma Valley, overlooking the Gila Valley.
to the east of the main part of Yuma.
Really, Yuma sits kind of like a pointed.
The north part is the point of a triangle, the south part being the bottom side of the triangle.
And that's the southern end.
And the town stretches off to the east.
And the college site for the community college was located off to the east of downtown about
four to five miles east along the edge of the Mesa and at an access point to the freeway.
Then the freeway had to cross the Gila River on a bridge.
Yes, well actually across the Colorado, the Gila already had spilled into the Gila, into the Colorado River.
So those were perhaps the three
principal things there.
We did some work in northern part of Yuma County and Quartzsite and in Parker, but that area has since been separated off from about three quarters away north from Yuma up the
Yuma Gunnery Range and Yuma Proving Grounds, which is the hot weather proving ground, Fort Churchill and Canada being the cold weather proving grounds for the Defense Department.
And the northern part now is La Paz County.
Fort Churchill is on Hudson Bay, isn't it?
Yes, right.
Where the polar bears are.
Right.
And so the men would get transferred and their families from Fort Churchill in the winter to Yuma in the summer.
No.
That's unfair.
One extreme to the other.
It would have been bad the other way, but they didn't see it that way.
But during that time, we had good cooperation with the people at Yuma Proving Ground, which was basically Army-operated for the Defense Department.
and with the Marine Corps Auxiliary Air Station staff, did not have a lot of contact with them, but where there was an essential contact, I must say it was always very, very positive.
I never had a negative experience with any of the military personnel.
The same was true at Bergstrom Air Force Base in Austin.
Never had a negative situation there.
The other aspect of being in Yuma was that
I also had a chance to help in getting a planning program.
I guess you might say getting some blood put into the planning program in Nogales, Arizona.
The planning director had been hired.

He did not know much of what it was all about, and so he got steered to me, and I sat and worked with him for several days and then went and visited him in Nogales and tried to help him get things set up there.
Nogales, Arizona is very small.
Nogales, Sonora is fairly large by comparison.
The Arizona side is 6,000 or 8,000, maybe 10,000 people.
The Sonora side was in the neighborhood of 60,000 to 80,000 people.
And being a port of entry and all of that, it had its own problems, very unique to that area.
But having worked in El Paso and having
grown up in Tucson and having lived in Yuma, I had an appreciation of the border influences.
And frankly, I always found that very enjoyable.
The Hispanic culture I find very adaptable to my thoughts.
When you were in Yuma then, you had contact with San Luis.
Did not in official capacity.
It was only to the extent that might have some contact with people
who had business there or were going back and forth.
That's all.
Very little.
Did have some contact with the planning staff in El Centro, California.
El Centro was very, very small.
And I think they had one planner on board and one draftsman or something like that.
And that was it.
And that was just minimal contact over there.
Had some contact with planning staff in San Diego.
That was a completely different ballgame.
So really, we weren't talking the same thing.
One interesting fact.
At the time, in 1960 or 59, Arizona put in a requirement that all boats must be licensed.
Statewide requirement, such as we have in Texas.
time there were 49,000 people in total in Yuma County, the city and all the towns and all the unincorporated area.
When the initial registration period was completed, there were over 10,000 votes registered in Yuma County.
You would never believe it.
Out in the desert.
But it was the influence of the Colorado River.
And in fact, a man lived down the street from us who was the commander.
He was a reserve Coast Guard officer, and he was the commander of the Coast Guard Reserve Flotilla that literally patrolled the Colorado River from Yuma up to, well, about to Parker or Bullhead City.
a distance of about 150 miles.
Was there much recreation voting that went down to the Gulf of California?
Not much going that way, no.
It was, in fact, the major problems regionally, the major problems at that time centered on the conflict between the US and Mexico with respect to the question of water quality.
for the discharge of water into the Colorado River.

Arizona, Colorado, Utah were meeting the requirements in terms of quantity, but there was so much of a problem with the leaching of the ground that the salt content or the carbonate content was getting so high that in Mexico, below San Luis, there were
farms that literally had been extremely productive that were being wiped out because of the high salt content in the water.
And this was becoming a very, very sore point for Mexico in its relations with the US.
And that, in turn, prompted some actions on the part of the
authorities at Boulder Dam and Hoover Dam and at the other dams on the Gila River to release larger quantities of water to thin out the salt content going downstream.
Plus began, that was the beginning perhaps of some real effort on the part of the farming community in both the Gila Valley and the Yuma Valley to
find some better ways to utilize the water that they were taking from the river and from underground.
A lot of water was coming from underground sources.
The other remaining highlight of the experience in Yuma, though, was in the Welton Mohawk Valley.
There were a number of farmers
that were very much concerned with planting.
They believed in it.
They supported it through conservation districts.
In fact, many of them lived in Yuma, even though they owned places out in the Welton Mohawk, 60 to 80 miles away from town, and would commute daily out there to do their farming.
Of course, there were people who lived in the town of Welton
a relatively small number.
Terrible drinking water.
And how people put up with it, I don't know.
But anyway, they lived there.
Some of them did.
And I went out a couple of times and met with the people there, as I did with the farm community and some of the mining people.
And when I say mining people, I'm talking about hard rock miners that came out of the hills up in the Quartzside area in the northeastern
part of Yuma County.
And those folks believed in planning.
They were rugged individuals, but they saw the need to get together on major issues such as water conservation, water usage, depletion of soil, highway location issues, things of that sort.
And so they were very positive.
And I always could look to them if I had a real problem out in that area to get some good, solid, and very realistic answers to the issues, the problems that were at hand.
So I count that experience as being a very positive one.
Then in 1962, I left Yuma, went to the city of Phoenix as assistant planning director under John Beatty, who was planning director, chief of our advanced planning section,
was Gordon Wagner, who then moved to Florida.
I don't remember which city.
This was several years after I had left there.
And I was in Phoenix from 1962 to 1964.
Others of the key staff that I dealt with were Jim Talley in the subdivision area,
who was very astute and a good operator.
Jim Talley, who was in zoning and especially on special use permits and things of that sort, very good.
Bob Johnson, who was responsible for the subdivision planning process, and again conducted an operation which I was able to contribute a little to
in much the same way that we had managed to do in Austin.
So there was some bridging across between the experience in Austin and what we were able to do in practice in Phoenix.
One of the things that occurred, which was rather interesting, was

that through the zoning operation, and we had zoning hearings every week, either commission hearings or council hearings, with usually somewhere in the neighborhood of 15 to 25 cases a week, which was a terrible load.
One of the things we were able to do was to regularize some of the hearing process
John Beatty and I worked on this.

And through the assistance of people like Bob Johnson and Jim Talley, we were able to bridge over some of these special use permit problems which went to the Board of Adjustment and the zoning issues.
And one area of practice that I first saw in Phoenix
was the idea of placing signs on the property and near the property under either zoning change consideration or board of adjustment consideration on a variance or special exception.
Signs about 18 by 24 inches or a little larger.
And these signs were color coded.

I recall blue for Board of Adjustment, pink for zoning, and later on I brought that idea to Fort Worth and it has since spread elsewhere in the state of Texas as a very practical way of letting the public know what was going on because legal ads generally don't take care of the real need.
There were also some things we did there in the notices including the sending of
frequently a map along on the zoning notice to people so they could physically see what the property was as it was going to be considered.
Gordon Wagner in the advanced planning section was in a dual role, not only responsible for that operation in the city's domain, but also worked with

two fellows, Gary Bourne, who was on loan from the Public Works Department, and another individual whose name I cannot, first name I can't recall, his name was Johnson, on loan from Traffic Engineering, and the three of them formed, were formed into what was called the Transportation Planning Team under the direction of Ed Hall, who at one time had been Traffic Engineer
for the city and or county of San Diego.
And Ed had come over for the purpose of trying to help determine the policies that should be established in the plan for transportation in Phoenix, and by greater implication, Maricopa County.
And from what I've seen in Phoenix, they could use a lot of transportation.
Right.
And that has been one of the problems, because the proposals that they came up with consistently got rejected by the politicos.
The Papago Freeway was one that they worked on very hard, did lots of documentation on, and it fell virtually on deaf ears.
Council members supported it, but the public did not.
And council members were never able to convince the citizens at large that this was a good thing to do.
And when it would get into the question of location and design and so on, and they'd have local area hearings, which occurred after I left, neighborhoods would rise up in opposition.
We want a freeway, but not next to our neighborhood.
And so many of the ideas that were developed just went by the boards, I'm sad to say.
However, what I did see there was something that I think every city ought to do, and that is to set aside a group of people with the full backing of top management,
as a coordinating body in the field of transportation planning.
They were able to do things.
And even though your comment is well taken, Phoenix needs a lot to be done.
But what you see today on the ground, what has been accomplished, in part has been accomplished because of the Arizona State Highway Department.
But in large measure, even these
rather mechanistic kinds of changes that have been made were accomplished simply because of that transportation planning team.

It was the first time that you really got three departments with key personnel working together, battling out ideas, hashing out this, hashing out that, deciding these are the hardcore issues, here are decent alternatives,
presenting those to their department heads, and those department heads, in turn, presenting them to the city manager and the city council.
It meant a lot of study, a lot of investigation, a lot of time by people who had the intellectual background, the knowledge base to deal with the things.
But what was lacking was somebody, and I think this is often a fault in city
in the council manager plan of government, somebody who was in the role of the community relations expert.
They had the technical know-how, and they had the community needs assessment know-how.
They just didn't have anybody to go out and explain to the public at large, here's why you need to do all these things.
Yes, it is going to hurt this area.
But here's the benefit for the total city.
Yeah, they need someone to point out the consequences of the various alternatives.
And if we do this, then this is going to happen.
And this will be good, and this will be not so good.
But I think this is the one thing that I saw as a function of city government, which frankly, I was very pleased with.
I would say the one thing.

Disappointment, though, was that Ed Hall, as the coordinator or the person in charge of the team, and he had other responsibilities too, but as the coordinator of that team, he had a rather brusque manner, a know-it-all manner that projected to the public that they weren't going to be listened to.
And that was too bad because Ed was really relying on those fellows who had lived there.
They knew the community.
They knew the problems.
They were good technicians.
They were very professional.
Two of them were registered professional engineers.
Gordon had been at it for five, six, seven years.
He was a Harvard planning program graduate.
Every reason.
in the world to think that things could have come out right.
In fact, I think he had spent some time in Minneapolis also on the planning staff, as I recall.
I'm not sure of that.
That's a tough agency to get into.
Up there?
Yes.
Once you're in that agency, no one leaves.
Well, he had left for health reasons.
Literally, he and his wife both had health problems and so on.
moved to Phoenix.

But I was in Phoenix two years, and frankly I left because the opportunity arrived to work under a city manager that had been in Cookingham's backyard, as it were, trained under LP Cookingham in Kansas City.
That was the primary reason I departed in 64 to move to Fort Worth.

I can't say really with respect to the Phoenix experience that there was much else other than my involvement in trying to regularize some of the subdivision planning process and to help a couple of community interests
One, I did sit as the planning director's representative to the high-rise study committee, which included a number of people who were interested in the development of high-rise buildings.
In fact, the chairman of the committee was a man from Colwell Banker who had moved over from Los Angeles just six months before he became chairman of that committee, a very astute person.
In fact, he one time described Phoenix like a Hollywood set, all false fronts.
For somebody coming from Los Angeles and Hollywood, I thought that was a very understandable statement.
But I guess the only other experience that I had there that I can really look to as being a particularly
profitable one was in working with, again, Parks and Recreation Department on some of their rather detailed problems, on-site location problems.
Was there any concern over air pollution at that time?
Not in Phoenix at that time, no.
The concerns were more water
Phoenix, in fact, experienced flooding there on the river, pretty extensive flooding, in fact, between Sky Harbor Airport and downtown, although downtown is not really at the river.
But there were those problems, and we also had some needs for coordination
with the county in the work that was being done out in the suburban areas.
That was fair to Midland cooperation.
There was always some conflict, though, beneath the surface between John Beatty and the county planning director.
Both of them were pretty long-term entrenched in their positions.

the county planning director's name i can't think of right now don well anyway whatever uh but i knew that john baity was going to be around for a good long time so i decided it was better to just depart although he when i left we were on extremely good terms and he encouraged me to stay so i i could have stayed there indefinitely but i wanted a chance to work in a in a little different
management situation in fact the manager in phoenix at that time was the brother of the man
